
# Text Encoding Techniques in NLP

## 1. One-Hot Encoding
- Represents each word as a binary vector with a single 1 and rest 0s
- Creates very sparse, high-dimensional vectors
- Simple but memory-intensive for large vocabularies
- Vocabulary size determines vector dimensionality
- No semantic relationships captured between words

## 2. Bag of Words (BoW)
- Counts word occurrences in a document, ignoring word order
- Creates a fixed-size vector of word frequencies
- Loses word sequence and grammatical information
- Simple frequency-based representation
- Foundation for many traditional NLP algorithms

## 3. TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency)
- Weighs word importance based on frequency in document and rarity across corpus
- Higher weights for distinctive words, lower for common words
- Useful for information retrieval and text classification
- Reduces impact of frequently occurring words
- Mathematical formula: TF × IDF

## 4. Count Vectorization
- Similar to BoW but optimized for counting word occurrences
- Produces sparse vectors using efficient data structures
- Good for fast text representation and processing
- Often used with scikit-learn's CountVectorizer
- Supports n-gram features and stop word removal

## 5. Hash Vectorization
- Uses hashing to map words to fixed-size vectors
- Reduces memory usage and handles unknown words
- May cause hash collisions (different words map to same index)
- No vocabulary storage required
- Useful for streaming data and large datasets

## 6. Integer/Ordinal Encoding
- Maps each unique word to a unique integer
- Compact representation useful for neural networks
- Order matters for sequential models
- Simple mapping: word → integer ID
- Often used as input to embedding layers

## 7. N-grams
- Captures sequences of n consecutive words/characters
- Bigrams (2-grams), Trigrams (3-grams), etc.
- Preserves some word order information
- Increases feature space dimensionality
- Useful for capturing local context and phrases

## 8. Character-Level Encoding
- Encodes text at the character level instead of words
- Useful for handling misspellings, rare words, and morphology
- Longer sequences but handles any input text
- Robust to out-of-vocabulary issues
- Often used with CNNs for text classification

## 9. Subword Tokenization
- **BPE (Byte Pair Encoding)**: Merges frequent character pairs iteratively
- **WordPiece**: Used in BERT, likelihood-based merging
- **SentencePiece**: Language-independent approach
- Balances vocabulary size and sequence length
- Enables handling of rare words and morphological variations




